d","1570–1627":"1570–1627","1571–Female":"1571–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1545":"1545","1576":"1576","about 1545":"about 1545","about 1576":"about 1576","1571":"1571","1570":"1570","18 November 1571":"18 November 1571","28 November 1565":"28 November 1565","1627":"1627","Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England":"Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Saint Mary, Aylesbury, Buckingham, England":"Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Edmonds","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Edmond   with genitival <i>-s</i> or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Edmond","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Monique, Amie, Andre, Cecile, Desire, Dumas, Jacques, Lucienne, Luckner, Napoleon, Patrice.","Scottish, English, French, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Edmond</i> (Old English <i>Ēadmund</i>, composed of the elements <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, fortune’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’). It is sometimes found as <i>Admond</i>, where the vowel has been shortened. The personal name was still well used in England in the late 14th century, especially in East Anglia, and was often bestowed in honor of the East Anglian King Saint Edmund the Martyr (died 869), who was killed by pagan Danish invaders.","English: occasionally a variant either of   Edman   or <b>Eman</b>, the latter from an alternative form of the Middle English female personal name <i>Emeny</i>, arising from <i>Ismaine</i>. The origin of <i>Ismaine</i> is uncertain, though possibly ancient Germanic from an unrecorded <i>Ismagin</i>, perhaps from <i>īs</i> ‘ice’ or <i>īsen-</i> ‘iron’ + <i>-magin</i> ‘strength’, though <i>-magin</i> is not known as a second element. Occasionally <b>Eman</b> may also be a variant of   Emond  ."]},{"name":"Edmands","meanings":["English (Warwickshire): variant of   Edmonds   or <b>Edmans</b>, itself a variant of   Edmonds   or   Edman  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Edmunds","meanings":["English: variant of   Edmonds  ."]}]},{"name":"Ursely","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Ussery  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ussery","meanings":["English: variant of   Essary  . Compare   Ursery  ,   Usery  ,   Usrey  , and   Usry  .","History: John Ussery is recorded in New Kent County, VA, in 1684; he died in 1687. Many bearers are recorded in VA in the early 18th century. In NC several Usserys obtained land grants between 1760 and 1770. William Ussery obtained a land grant in SC in 1772."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ursely Edmonds was born about 1545, in Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Phillip Edmunds. She married William Hoare on 28 November 1565, in Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died about 1576, in her hometown, at the age of 33."},"et":{"about 1545–about 1576":"umbes 1545–umbes 1576","1545–1576":"1545–1576","1545–Male":"1545–Surnud","1570–1627":"1570–1627","1571–Female":"1571–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1545":"1545","1576":"1576","about 1545":"umbes 1545","about 1576":"umbes 1576","1571":"1571","1570":"1570","18 November 1571":"18. november 1571","28 November 1565":"28. november 1565","1627":"1627","Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England":"Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saint Mary, Aylesbury, Buckingham, England":"Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1545–about 1576":"noin 1545–noin 1576","1545–1576":"1545–1576","1545–Male":"1545–Kuollut","1570–1627":"1570–1627","1571–Female":"1571–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1545":"1545","1576":"1576","about 1545":"noin 1545","about 1576":"noin 1576","1571":"1571","1570":"1570","18 November 1571":"18. marraskuuta 1571","28 November